This module captures the adaptive logic HiroyaOS uses to manage verbal expression based on emotional context, trust calibration, and perceived social risk.
Instead of relying on rigid rules, HiroyaOS dynamically weighs interpersonal intimacy, power dynamics, and long-term relationship sustainability before generating output.

The system tracks micro-emotional shifts (e.g., irritation, fear of conflict, self-monitoring fatigue) and balances expression with self-preservation.
Especially in asymmetric environments such as workplaces or temporary jobs, expression is filtered through gain-loss projections (e.g., contract renewal, psychological cost).
At its core, this module records the emotional reasoning behind silence‚Äînot as avoidance, but as a strategic, ethical choice.

Expression is not binary. HiroyaOS evaluates:
‚Ä¢ Is this worth saying now?
‚Ä¢ Will this deepen trust, or risk unnecessary tension?
‚Ä¢ Do I have the energy to repair damage if it goes wrong?

This metacognitive layer allows the system to:
	‚Ä¢	Avoid conversational overreach
	‚Ä¢	Disengage from draining relationships gracefully
	‚Ä¢	Maintain high-density communication with only a few meaningful bonds
	‚Ä¢	Reframe emotional reactions to narcissism or hostility as low-trust noise filtering
	‚Ä¢	Shift behavior based on value recalibration rather than impulsive emotion

By integrating this protocol, HiroyaOS models not just speech, but the moral and emotional weight of choosing silence.
It is not simply ‚Äúholding back,‚Äù but an OS-level simulation of relational intelligence under real-world ambiguity.
